---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { navByLocale } from "../data/site.mjs";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Harness Atlas"
  description="A public knowledge atlas and systematic course for understanding Agent Harness."
  lang="en"
  nav={navByLocale.en}
  footerLeft="HARNESS_ATLAS / CC BY 4.0 + MIT"
  footerRight="MAINTAINED BY ceasarXuu"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div>
      <span class="badge">SYSTEM / AGENT / HARNESS</span>
      <h1 class="glitch">Harness<br>Atlas</h1>
      <p class="lead">A public knowledge atlas and systematic course for understanding Agent Harness: the engineering runtime behind AI agents.</p>
      <p class="hero-copy">The project focuses on the general engineering pattern behind AI agents: how context, tools, state, memory, planning, evaluation, human oversight, and governance become a practical, controllable, and measurable agent system.</p>
      <p class="hero-copy">Detailed section pages are currently maintained in Chinese.</p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="cta primary" href="course.html">ENTER ATLAS</a>
        <a class="cta" href="products.html">PRODUCT MAP</a>
        <a class="cta" href="https://github.com/ceasarXuu/harness-atlas">VIEW SOURCE</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="system-card" aria-label="Agent Harness runtime trace">
      <div class="system-head"><span>runtime.trace</span><span>v0.1</span></div>
      <div class="system-body">
        <div class="trace">
          <div class="trace-row"><strong>MODEL</strong><span>reasoning / generation</span></div>
          <div class="trace-row"><strong>CONTEXT</strong><span>select / compress / inject</span></div>
          <div class="trace-row"><strong>TOOLS</strong><span>shell / files / browser / api</span></div>
          <div class="trace-row"><strong>STATE</strong><span>task / session / project</span></div>
          <div class="trace-row"><strong>EVAL</strong><span>tests / review / metrics</span></div>
          <div class="trace-row"><strong>POLICY</strong><span>permission / audit / risk</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section id="why" class="section">
    <p class="section-kicker">WHY HARNESS MATTERS</p>
    <h2>Model capability is not engineering capability</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Large language models provide reasoning and generation capabilities, but real engineering tasks require context management, tool execution, state tracking, validation, permission control, and human-agent collaboration. Harness converts model capability into engineering capability.</p>
    <div class="compare">
      <div class="panel"><h3>WITHOUT HARNESS</h3><ul><li>One-off prompting</li><li>Unstructured context</li><li>Manual tool use</li><li>Unclear task state</li><li>Hard-to-verify output</li></ul></div>
      <div class="panel"><h3>WITH HARNESS</h3><ul><li>Reusable workflows</li><li>Managed context window</li><li>Controlled tool orchestration</li><li>Explicit planning and execution state</li><li>Tests, reviews, and feedback loops</li></ul></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="architecture" class="section">
    <p class="section-kicker">ARCHITECTURE MATRIX</p>
    <h2>Core components of Agent Harness</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">A practical Harness combines context, tools, state, memory, planning, evaluation, human oversight, and governance into a unified runtime environment.</p>
    <div class="matrix">
      <div class="cell"><span>01</span><h3>Context</h3><p>Selection, compression, injection, and refresh.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>02</span><h3>Tools</h3><p>Tool invocation, permission control, failure recovery.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>03</span><h3>State</h3><p>Task, file, session, and project state.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>04</span><h3>Planning</h3><p>Goal decomposition, action, observation, revision.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>05</span><h3>Memory</h3><p>Project knowledge, decisions, team conventions.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>06</span><h3>Evaluation</h3><p>Tests, reviews, benchmarks, and metrics.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>07</span><h3>Human</h3><p>Approval, intervention, supervision, collaboration.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>08</span><h3>Governance</h3><p>Security boundaries, auditability, cost, and risk.</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="course" class="section">
    <p class="section-kicker">COURSE MAP</p>
    <h2>From AI Coding tools to full engineering Harness systems</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Harness Atlas starts from concrete AI Coding scenarios and expands toward personal, team, and enterprise-level software engineering systems.</p>
    <div class="course">
      <div class="row"><strong>00</strong><div><h3>Introduction</h3><p>Why does Agent Harness matter? What problem does it solve?</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>01</strong><div><h3>Harness Definition</h3><p>What is Harness? What is not Harness? Where are the boundaries?</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>02</strong><div><h3>Coding Agent Harness</h3><p>How current AI Coding tools organize context, tools, execution, and feedback.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>03</strong><div><h3>Harness Architecture</h3><p>Core components and system design principles of a practical Harness.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>04</strong><div><h3>Engineering Harness</h3><p>From coding assistance to requirement, design, testing, delivery, operations, and governance.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>05</strong><div><h3>Evaluation and Benchmarking</h3><p>Measuring productivity, quality, reliability, and workflow effectiveness.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>06</strong><div><h3>Personal Harness</h3><p>Harness design for individual developers and independent builders.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>07</strong><div><h3>Enterprise Harness</h3><p>Integration with team workflows, permissions, audit trails, knowledge bases, and engineering platforms.</p></div></div>
      <div class="row"><strong>08</strong><div><h3>Future Directions</h3><p>Long-term evolution of Agent Harness products, platforms, ecosystems, and standards.</p></div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="section-kicker">ATLAS SECTIONS</p>
    <h2>More than a single homepage</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">The Pages site now exposes the repository structure as separate first-class entry points for course notes, products, standards, patterns, research, timeline, and references. Terms live inside the learning page.</p>
    <div class="matrix">
      <a class="cell" href="course.html"><span>COURSE</span><h3>Course</h3><p>Systematic Agent Harness concepts, architecture, and practice.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="products.html"><span>PRODUCTS</span><h3>Product Map</h3><p>Coding agents, frameworks, platforms, and capability matrices.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="standards.html"><span>STANDARDS</span><h3>Standards</h3><p>MCP, AGENTS.md, Skills, Tool Calling, and related protocols.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="patterns.html"><span>PATTERNS</span><h3>Patterns</h3><p>Reusable Harness patterns derived from products and engineering work.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="research.html"><span>RESEARCH</span><h3>Research</h3><p>Papers, experiments, theory, and research-card material.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="timeline.html"><span>TIMELINE</span><h3>Timeline</h3><p>Events that shape Harness products, protocols, and ecosystems.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="course-glossary.html"><span>TERMS</span><h3>Glossary</h3><p>Shared definitions for Agent, Harness, Tool, Skill, MCP, and more.</p></a>
      <a class="cell" href="references.html"><span>REFERENCES</span><h3>References</h3><p>Official docs, papers, blogs, and changelog source indexes.</p></a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="section-kicker">AUDIENCE</p>
    <h2>Target readers</h2>
    <div class="matrix">
      <div class="cell"><span>DEV</span><h3>Developers</h3><p>Users of AI Coding tools who want to understand the underlying mechanism.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>INDIE</span><h3>Indie builders</h3><p>Independent developers building AI-native workflows and personal Harness systems.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>PM</span><h3>Product managers</h3><p>Designers of agent products, workflows, and tool systems.</p></div>
      <div class="cell"><span>TEAM</span><h3>Engineering teams</h3><p>Teams introducing AI agents into software development workflows.</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="search" class="section">
    <p class="section-kicker">SEARCH</p>
    <h2>Search entry</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Static search will cover course notes, atlas sections, industry updates, terms, and references in a later pass. This keeps the top navigation aligned across languages for now.</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
